  <div class="content-container">
    <h1>Data Processing</h1>
    <h3>
      Live data feeds from public sources such as NASA, NOAA, USGS, METEOSTAT are processed to create input files for the the visualization engine.  Here cloud density data has been transformed into a normal map, which is used to seed the generative cloud system.
    </h3>

    <div class="img-container">
      <img src="/images/clouds.jpg">
    </div>
  </div> 
  
    <hr>
  
  <div class="content-container">
    <h1>Visualization Engine</h1>
    <h3>
      The prepared files are fed into custom shaders, which are used to create rendered layers such as night lighting, ocean reflectivity, cloud height, and atmospheric density. The various layers are then combined in realtime to create the final rendered view.
    </h3>

    <div class="img-container">
      <img src="/images/tiles.jpg">
    </div>
    </div>

    <hr>

  <div class="content-container">
    <h1>Ultra-high Resolution Output</h1>
    <h3>
      The resolution of the final visualization will be roughly equivalent to 16 times HD (roughly comparable to 4 times 4K resolution), going beyond the perceptual abilities of the human eye to create as real a visual experience as possible.

    </h3>

    <div class="img-container">
      <img src="/images/resolution.jpg">
    </div>
